  "verdict": "ORANGE->CLOSED-NEGATIVE: KV-split CLOSES the small-N occupancy gap (N=512: 32->128 CTAs, intra-framework 2.53x, reaching parity with round-4 single-kernel) but is a SMALL-N-ONLY lever -- its benefit saturates once N alone fills the 48 SMs while its partial-O HBM round-trip cost grows as O(N*split*d). No decomposition beats cuBLAS; best ratio 3.47x @ N=512. The GEMM-tile-efficiency wall (round-4 finding) is confirmed fundamental and KV-split does not breach it.",
  "pattern_observations": [
    "KV-split helps small-N by 2.53x (N=512 intra-framework, 32->128 CTAs) -- the user hypothesis is CONFIRMED for the under-occupied regime.",
    "KV-split benefit saturates at the split K where ctas_partial >= ~48 SMs (N=512 plateaus at kv=4=128 CTAs; kv=8/16 REGRESS due to merge + over-subscription).",
    "At N>=2048 the grid is already saturated by N/Bq alone, so KV-split adds only the HBM partial-O tax: decomp-best 0.668ms vs round-4 single-kernel 0.245ms @ N=2048 (2.7x WORSE).",
    "BK=256 (round-4 finding) confirmed best within every fixed (N,Bq,kv) -- wider KV tile amortizes softmax (e.g. N=512 kv=1: BK64 0.156 -> BK256 0.146).",
    "Bq>16 (more query rows/CTA, serial sub-tiles, ONE warp) is uniformly SLOWER -- it cuts grid count, the opposite of what small-N needs. Bq=16 dominates at small N.",
    "softmax-overhead floor: even at max occupancy the per-16x16-tile online-softmax keeps the fused path ~3.4x above cuBLAS huge-tile GEMM -- the round-4 binding constraint is re-confirmed, not breached by any decomposition."
  ],
